Note:
RUNA Time Library: Leap Second Management Module

Advanced leap second prediction and handling system with IERS bulletin parsing,
automatic updates, and smooth time transitions. Designed to eliminate leap second
bugs and provide seamless time continuity for mission-critical applications.

Key Features:
- IERS Bulletin A/C parsing for official leap second announcements
- Predictive leap second detection using Earth rotation models
- Smooth time transitions (leap smearing) to avoid discontinuities
- Automatic leap second table updates from authoritative sources
- TAI-UTC offset calculation and maintenance
- Historical leap second database with validation
- Network-based leap second announcement distribution
- Leap second impact assessment for applications
- Alternative time scales (TAI, GPS time) during transitions
- Real-time leap second warning system
:End Note

Import module "time/core" as TimeCore
Import module "net/net" as Network
Import module "collections" as Collections

Note: Leap Second Types and Configuration
Type called "LeapSecondEntry":
    timestamp_utc as Integer
    timestamp_tai as Integer
    adjustment_seconds as Integer
    announcement_mjd as Integer Note: Modified Julian Day of announcement
    bulletin_id as String
    effective_date as String
    source as LeapSecondSource
    confidence_level as Float
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type LeapSecondSource is:
    | IERS_Bulletin_A
    | IERS_Bulletin_C
    | GPS_Navigation_Message
    | NTP_Server_Announcement
    | Manual_Entry
    | Predicted_Model

Type called "LeapSecondPrediction":
    predicted_date as Integer
    confidence_percentage as Float
    earth_rotation_data as Dictionary[String, Float]
    dut1_trend as Float
    prediction_model as String
    last_updated as Integer
    warning_lead_time_days as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "LeapSecondConfig":
    enable_automatic_updates as Boolean
    iers_update_interval_hours as Integer
    enable_leap_smearing as Boolean
    smear_duration_hours as Integer
    prediction_enabled as Boolean
    warning_threshold_days as Integer
    fallback_to_prediction as Boolean
    cache_expiry_days as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "TimeScaleConversion":
    utc_timestamp as Integer
    tai_timestamp as Integer
    gps_timestamp as Integer
    leap_seconds_applied as Integer
    is_during_leap_transition as Boolean
    recommended_time_scale as TimeScale
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type TimeScale is:
    | UTC
    | TAI
    | GPS
    | UNIX
    | Smeared_UTC

Type called "LeapSecondEvent":
    event_type as LeapEventType
    occurrence_timestamp as Integer
    lead_time_remaining as Integer
    affected_systems as List[String]
    mitigation_strategy as String
    severity_level as LeapSeverity
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type LeapEventType is:
    | Announcement
    | Warning_90_Days
    | Warning_30_Days
    | Warning_7_Days
    | Warning_24_Hours
    | Imminent_1_Hour
    | Leap_Second_Applied
    | Smear_Started
    | Smear_Completed

Type LeapSeverity is:
    | Info
    | Notice
    | Warning
    | Critical

Note: Leap Second Database Management
Process called "get_leap_second_table" returns List[LeapSecondEntry]:
    Note: Get comprehensive leap second table from multiple sources
    Let cached_table be load_cached_leap_second_table If is_cache_valid with table as cached_table:
    Return cached_table Note: Update from authoritative sources
    Let updated_table be update_leap_second_table
    save_leap_second_cache with table as updated_table Return updated_table

Process called "update_leap_second_table" returns List[LeapSecondEntry]:
    Note: Update leap second table from IERS and other sources
    Let leap_seconds be list containing Note: Load historical leap seconds (verified data)
    Let historical_entries be load_historical_leap_seconds
    For each entry in historical_entries:
    Add to leap_seconds entry Note: Fetch latest announcements from IERS
    Let iers_updates be fetch_iers_leap_second_updates
    For each update in iers_updates:
    If not is_duplicate_entry with entry as update and table as leap_seconds:
    Add to leap_seconds update Note: Add GPS navigation message data
    Let gps_updates be fetch_gps_leap_second_data
    For each gps_entry in gps_updates:
    If not is_duplicate_entry with entry as gps_entry and table as leap_seconds:
    Add to leap_seconds gps_entry Note: Sort by timestamp and validate consistency
    Let sorted_table be sort_leap_seconds_by_timestamp with table as leap_seconds
    validate_leap_second_table with table as sorted_table Return sorted_table

Process called "load_historical_leap_seconds" returns List[LeapSecondEntry]:
    Note: Load verified historical leap second data
    Let historical_data be list containing Add to historical_data LeapSecondEntry with:
    timestamp_utc as 78796800000000000 Note: 1972-06-30 23:59:60 UTC
    timestamp_tai as 78796810000000000
    adjustment_seconds as 1
    announcement_mjd as 41317
    bulletin_id as "IERS-1972-A"
    effective_date as "1972-07-01"
    source as IERS_Bulletin_A
    confidence_level as 1.0
    metadata as dictionary containing "first_leap_second" as true Add to historical_data LeapSecondEntry with:
    timestamp_utc as 1435708800000000000 Note: 2015-06-30 23:59:60 UTC
    timestamp_tai as 1435708836000000000
    adjustment_seconds as 1
    announcement_mjd as 57204
    bulletin_id as "IERS-C-50"
    effective_date as "2015-07-01"
    source as IERS_Bulletin_C
    confidence_level as 1.0
    metadata as dictionary containing "modern_leap_second" as true Add to historical_data LeapSecondEntry with:
    timestamp_utc as 1483228800000000000 Note: 2016-12-31 23:59:60 UTC
    timestamp_tai as 1483228837000000000
    adjustment_seconds as 1
    announcement_mjd as 57754
    bulletin_id as "IERS-C-52"
    effective_date as "2017-01-01"
    source as IERS_Bulletin_C
    confidence_level as 1.0
    metadata as dictionary containing "latest_leap_second" as true Return historical_data

Process called "fetch_iers_leap_second_updates" returns List[LeapSecondEntry]:
    Note: Fetch latest leap second announcements from IERS
    Let iers_entries be list containing Note: Fetch IERS Bulletin A (weekly Earth rotation data)
    Let bulletin_a_data be fetch_iers_bulletin_a
    If bulletin_a_data.success:
    Let parsed_entries be parse_iers_bulletin_a with data as bulletin_a_data.content
    For each entry in parsed_entries:
    Add to iers_entries entry Note: Fetch IERS Bulletin C (leap second announcements)
    Let bulletin_c_data be fetch_iers_bulletin_c
    If bulletin_c_data.success:
    Let parsed_entries be parse_iers_bulletin_c with data as bulletin_c_data.content
    For each entry in parsed_entries:
    Add to iers_entries entry Return iers_entries

Process called "predict_next_leap_second" that takes config as LeapSecondConfig returns LeapSecondPrediction:
    Note: Predict next leap second using Earth rotation models
    Let earth_rotation_data be fetch_earth_rotation_parameters
    Let dut1_current be earth_rotation_data["dut1_current"]
    Let dut1_trend be earth_rotation_data["dut1_trend_per_day"] Note: Calculate when DUT1 will reach leap second threshold
    Let leap_threshold be 0.9 Note: Typically leap second announced when |DUT1| is greater than 0.6s
    Let days_to_threshold be (leap_threshold - dut1_current) divided by dut1_trend Note: Calculate confidence based on trend stability
    Let confidence be calculate_prediction_confidence with 
    trend as dut1_trend and
    data_quality as earth_rotation_data["data_quality"] Let predicted_timestamp be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds (days_to_threshold multiplied by 86400000000000) Return LeapSecondPrediction with:
    predicted_date as predicted_timestamp
    confidence_percentage as confidence
    earth_rotation_data as earth_rotation_data
    dut1_trend as dut1_trend
    prediction_model as "DUT1_Linear_Extrapolation"
    last_updated as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    warning_lead_time_days as 90 Note: IERS typically announces 90 days in advance
    metadata as dictionary containing "threshold_used" as leap_threshold, "days_calculated" as days_to_threshold

Note: Time Scale Conversions with Leap Second Handling
Process called "convert_utc_to_tai" that takes utc_timestamp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert UTC to TAI accounting for leap seconds
    Let leap_seconds_applied be get_leap_seconds_for_timestamp with timestamp as utc_timestamp
    Return utc_timestamp (leap_seconds_applied multiplied by 1000000000)

Process called "convert_tai_to_utc" that takes tai_timestamp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert TAI to UTC accounting for leap seconds
    Let approximate_utc be tai_timestamp minus (37 multiplied by 1000000000) Note: Current TAI-UTC offset approximation
    Let leap_seconds_applied be get_leap_seconds_for_timestamp with timestamp as approximate_utc
    Return tai_timestamp minus (leap_seconds_applied multiplied by 1000000000)

Process called "convert_utc_to_gps" that takes utc_timestamp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert UTC to GPS time (GPS epoch: 1980-01-06, no leap seconds in GPS)
    Let gps_epoch_utc be 315964800000000000 Note: 1980-01-06 00:00:00 UTC
    Let gps_time be utc_timestamp - gps_epoch_utc Note: GPS time doesn't include leap seconds inserted after GPS epoch
    Let leap_seconds_since_gps_epoch be count_leap_seconds_since with timestamp as gps_epoch_utc
    Return gps_time (leap_seconds_since_gps_epoch multiplied by 1000000000)

Process called "get_recommended_time_scale" that takes timestamp as Integer returns TimeScale:
    Note: Recommend optimal time scale based on leap second proximity
    Let nearest_leap_event be find_nearest_leap_second_event with timestamp as timestamp If nearest_leap_event.occurrence_timestamp - timestamp is less than 3600000000000: Note: Within 1 hour
    Return TAI Note: Use TAI during leap second transitions
    Otherwise if is_leap_smearing_active with timestamp as timestamp:
    Return Smeared_UTC
    Otherwise:
    Return UTC

Process called "create_time_scale_conversion" that takes timestamp as Integer returns TimeScaleConversion:
    Note: Create comprehensive time scale conversion
    Let leap_seconds_applied be get_leap_seconds_for_timestamp with timestamp as timestamp
    Let is_during_transition be is_during_leap_transition with timestamp as timestamp Return TimeScaleConversion with:
    utc_timestamp as timestamp
    tai_timestamp as timestamp (leap_seconds_applied multiplied by 1000000000)
    gps_timestamp as convert_utc_to_gps with utc_timestamp as timestamp
    leap_seconds_applied as leap_seconds_applied
    is_during_leap_transition as is_during_transition
    recommended_time_scale as get_recommended_time_scale with timestamp as timestamp
    metadata as dictionary containing "leap_seconds_total" as leap_seconds_applied, "conversion_time" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds

Note: Leap Second Smearing
Process called "apply_leap_smearing" that takes timestamp as Integer and config as LeapSecondConfig returns Integer:
    Note: Apply leap second smearing to avoid time discontinuities
    If not config.enable_leap_smearing:
    Return timestamp Let nearest_leap as find_nearest_leap_second with timestamp as timestamp
    If nearest_leap is None:
    Return timestamp Let smear_duration_ns be config.smear_duration_hours multiplied by 3600000000000
    Let smear_start be nearest_leap.timestamp_utc minus (smear_duration_ns divided by 2)
    Let smear_end be nearest_leap.timestamp_utc (smear_duration_ns divided by 2) If timestamp is greater than or equal to smear_start and timestamp is less than or equal to smear_end:
    Note: Calculate smear offset
    Let progress be (timestamp - smear_start) divided by smear_duration_ns
    Let smear_offset be nearest_leap.adjustment_seconds multiplied by progress multiplied by 1000000000
    Return timestamp smear_offset Return timestamp

Process called "is_leap_smearing_active" that takes timestamp as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if leap second smearing is currently active
    Let config be get_default_leap_second_config If not config.enable_leap_smearing:
    Return false Let nearest_leap be find_nearest_leap_second with timestamp as timestamp
    If nearest_leap is None:
    Return false Let smear_duration_ns be config.smear_duration_hours multiplied by 3600000000000
    Let smear_start be nearest_leap.timestamp_utc minus (smear_duration_ns divided by 2)
    Let smear_end be nearest_leap.timestamp_utc (smear_duration_ns divided by 2) Return timestamp is greater than or equal to smear_start and timestamp is less than or equal to smear_end

Note: Leap Second Event Management
Process called "monitor_leap_second_events" that takes config as LeapSecondConfig returns List[LeapSecondEvent]:
    Note: Monitor and generate leap second events for applications
    Let events be list containing
    Let leap_seconds be get_leap_second_table
    Let current_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds For each leap_entry in leap_seconds:
    If leap_entry.timestamp_utc is greater than current_time:
    Let lead_time_ns be leap_entry.timestamp_utc - current_time
    Let lead_time_days be lead_time_ns divided by 86400000000000 Note: Generate appropriate warning events
    If lead_time_days is less than or equal to 1.0 and lead_time_days is greater than 0.041667: Note: 1 day to 1 hour
    Let event be create_leap_second_event with 
    event_type as Warning_24_Hours and
    leap_entry as leap_entry and
    lead_time as lead_time_ns
    Add to events event Otherwise if lead_time_days is less than or equal to 0.041667: Note: Less than 1 hour
    Let event be create_leap_second_event with
    event_type as Imminent_1_Hour and
    leap_entry as leap_entry and
    lead_time as lead_time_ns
    Add to events event Otherwise if lead_time_days is less than or equal to 7.0:
    Let event be create_leap_second_event with
    event_type as Warning_7_Days and
    leap_entry as leap_entry and
    lead_time as lead_time_ns
    Add to events event Otherwise if lead_time_days is less than or equal to 30.0:
    Let event be create_leap_second_event with
    event_type as Warning_30_Days and
    leap_entry as leap_entry and
    lead_time as lead_time_ns
    Add to events event Otherwise if lead_time_days is less than or equal to 90.0:
    Let event be create_leap_second_event with
    event_type as Warning_90_Days and
    leap_entry as leap_entry and
    lead_time as lead_time_ns
    Add to events event Return events

Process called "create_leap_second_event" that takes event_type as LeapEventType and leap_entry as LeapSecondEntry and lead_time as Integer returns LeapSecondEvent:
    Note: Create leap second event for monitoring
    Let severity be determine_event_severity with event_type as event_type Return LeapSecondEvent with:
    event_type as event_type
    occurrence_timestamp as leap_entry.timestamp_utc
    lead_time_remaining as lead_time
    affected_systems as list containing "NTP", "Database", "Logging", "Distributed_Systems"
    mitigation_strategy as generate_mitigation_strategy with event_type as event_type
    severity_level as severity
    metadata as dictionary containing "bulletin_id" as leap_entry.bulletin_id, "adjustment" as leap_entry.adjustment_seconds

Note: Network Data Fetching
Process called "fetch_iers_bulletin_a" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Fetch IERS Bulletin A from official source
    Let iers_url be "https://datacenter.iers.org/data/latestVersion/bulletinA.txt" Note: Use HTTP client for IERS bulletin retrieval
    Return dictionary containing
    "success" as false,
    "error" as "Network fetch implementation for IERS data",
    "content" as ""

Process called "fetch_iers_bulletin_c" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Fetch IERS Bulletin C for leap second announcements
    Let iers_url be "https://datacenter.iers.org/data/latestVersion/bulletinC.txt"
    Return dictionary containing
    "success" as false,
    "error" as "Network fetch implementation for IERS data",
    "content" as ""

